Time Series Analysis.¶

This notebook uses the kaggle data (link) on stock prices for the MAANG companies - Meta, Apple, Amazon, Netflix and Google since their IPO.

For our study we focus on the closing values (USD) for business days focusing between fixed dates for easy standardisation.

This is a naive inplementation to practice the understanding of time series analysis.

We cover the following -

1 Initial Exploration
    * Standardising the data
    * Resampling using business days, months
    * Visualising

2 Statistical Analysis
    * Series decomposition - decompose the timesereis for each company data to check for Seasonality, Trend, and, Variance
    * ACF and PACF plots
    * Stationarity checks

1. Fitting time series models & forecasting 
    * using exponential smoothing  
    * using statsmodels
    * using Prophet 

2. Fitting using NN 
    * using SimpleRNN
    * using LSTM

Data constraints¶

We will set a minimum and a maximum date for the stock data. This will limit the analysis of the #MAANG dataset to a uniform timeline. The variable used for the analyis is the closing value of the stock for that day in US dollars $

For our purpose we chose format YYYY-MM-DD

min = '2019-01-01'
max = '2024-01-10'

In [ ]:
def standardiseData(dataFrame,minDate=minDate,maxDate=maxDate):

    new_index = pd.date_range(minDate,maxDate,freq='B') # dates between which we obderve the time Series

    dataFrame['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(dataFrame['Date'],yearfirst=True)
    dataFrame.set_index('Date',inplace=True)
    dataFrame = dataFrame[minDate:maxDate]

    newDF = dataFrame.reindex(new_index,method='bfill')

    newDF = newDF[['Close']]
    return newDF
In [ ]:
def checkData(df,minDate=minDate,maxDate=maxDate):

    days = len(pd.date_range(minDate,maxDate,freq='B'))

    assert len(df) == days
    assert df['Close'].dtypes == 'float64'
    assert df.index.dtype == '<M8[ns]'

    return None
In [ ]:
def create_AnalysisData(companyNames,logData=False):

    ## initialising the final Df to df_0 for merging with the others. 

    listDF = []
    final_cols = []
    for i in range(len(companyNames)):
        final_cols.append(companyNames[i])
        df_i = pd.read_csv(f'data/{companyNames[i]}_daily.csv', header=0)
        df_i = standardiseData(df_i)
        checkData(df_i)
        
        listDF.append(df_i)

    finalDF = pd.concat(listDF,ignore_index=False,axis=1)
    finalDF.columns = final_cols

    if logData:

        finalDF = finalDF.apply(np.log10,axis=0)

    return finalDF

def plot_decompose(TS,decomposition):
    ''' 
        this function plots the original time series along with the 
        trend,seasonaloty and residuls extracted from the decomposition model: 'multiplicative'
        
    '''
    est_trend = decomposition.trend 
    est_seasonality = decomposition.seasonal 
    est_residual = decomposition.resid 

    fig,axes = plt.subplots(4,1,sharex=True,sharey=False,figsize=(16,5))

    axes[0].plot(TS,label='Original')
    axes[0].legend(loc='upper left')

    axes[1].plot(est_trend,label='Trend')
    axes[1].legend(loc='upper left')

    axes[2].plot(est_seasonality,label='Seasonality')
    axes[2].legend(loc='upper left')

    axes[3].plot(est_residual,label='Residuals')
    axes[3].legend(loc='upper left')

    return est_trend,est_seasonality,est_residual

Smoothing using Exponential methods¶

Single Exponential - Captures neither trend or seasonality

    from statsmodels.tsa.api import SimpleExpSmoothing

Double Exponential - Captures trend

    from statsmodels.tsa.api import Holt

Triple Exponential - Captures both trend and seasonality

    from statsmodels.tsa.api import ExponentialSmoothing
In [ ]:
from statsmodels.tsa.api import SimpleExpSmoothing, Holt, ExponentialSmoothing

split_at = 100
train,test = timeSeriesData_rolling[company][:-split_at], timeSeriesData_rolling[company][-split_at:]
train_time,test_time = timeSeriesData_rolling.index.values[:-split_at], timeSeriesData_rolling.index.values[-split_at:]

## Single Exponential Smoothing 
singleExp = SimpleExpSmoothing(train).fit(optimized=True)
singleExp_pred = singleExp.forecast(len(test))

# Double Exponential Smoothing 
doubleExp = Holt(train).fit(optimized=True)
doubleExp_pred = doubleExp.forecast(len(test))

# Triple Exponential Smoothing
tripleExp = ExponentialSmoothing(train,
                                 trend='multiplicative',
                                 seasonal='multiplicative',
                                 seasonal_periods=13).fit(optimized=True)
tripleExp_pred = tripleExp.forecast(len(test))

Using Deep Learning¶

We will use the following methods to do the Deep Learning based forecasting of the time series

  1. Simple RNNs
  2. LSTM

But before we do any of that we need to prepare the data so that it can be used as an input for the Neural Networks framework.

[!NOTE] The input format required for RNN is a 3D numpy array : (n_samples,time_steps,n_features)

Since we only have 1 time series .. we will create multiple sample from it

And form a set for train_X, test_X, train_Y, test_y

[!WARNING]

The test_X should be of the same length as train_X :

Since a simpleRNN is a many-to-one architecture and should have a fixed input length

Parameters for preparing the input¶

We will have to create many samples from the train data to feed into the RNN. We do so by extracting a sequence of fixed sizes from the series with the output for that sequence being the next item after the sequence.

1. split_at : (int) Split the series into train and test parts 
2. input_size : (int) defines the size of the sequence input to be fed into the RNN 
3. step_size : steps to jump before the start of the next train sample from the entire train series.
In [ ]:
def convert_to_keras_format(series):
    ''' 
        this is to convert the series into keras acceptable format for RNNs 
        that is a 3-D array 
    '''
    series = np.array(series)

    return series.reshape(series.shape[0],series.shape[1],1)
In [ ]:
def train_test_split_(series, split_at=100, input_size=20, step_size=5):

    """ 
        Splits the data set in to training and test sets and converts the series into the 
        requires keras format i.e a 3-d array:

        ==========================================
        arguments - 

        series : data sets as a pandas series, or a list
        split_at : index from where to separate the train and test parts  -- beginning from the end
        input_size : fixed size of the input sequence to be fed into the RNN .. 
                     this means that if input_size=5 then RNN will learn the effect of last 5 steps 
                     in the series to predict the next step. 
        step_size: this is the jump needed to begin a new train sample from a different starting point. 
    """

    train,test = series[:-split_at], series[-split_at:]
    
    train_X,train_Y = [],[]

    for i in range(0,train.shape[0]-input_size,step_size):

        train_X.append(train[i:i+input_size])
        train_Y.append(train[i+input_size])

    train_X = convert_to_keras_format(train_X)
    train_Y = np.array(train_Y)

    test_x = test[:input_size]
    test_y = test[input_size:]

    return train_X,train_Y,test_x,test_y

def fit_simple_RNN(train_X,train_Y,cell_units=10,epochs=10):

    """ 
    Fits the SimpleRNN from tensorflow

    ==============================

    arguments : 

    train_X : training data with shape (n_samples,n_timesteps,n_features)
    train_Y : target variables for prediction
    cell_units : number of cells in the Sequential RNN
    epochs : number of epochs for which the model is to be trained

    """
    # initialising a model
    model = Sequential()

    ## construct a RNN layer with suer define number of cell unit 
    ## and input with fixed step size and 1 feature i.e the history of the series
    model.add(SimpleRNN(cell_units,input_shape=(train_X.shape[1],1)))

    ## ouput layer for predictions
    model.add(Dense(1))

    ## defining run parameters with epochs, loss and optimizer
    model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam')
    model.fit(train_X,train_Y,epochs=epochs, batch_size=64, verbose= 0)

    return model

Predictions -¶

[!TIP] To make predictions using the trained model we will use the text_X and test_y Remember we need to make predictions throughout the length of y , so we will iteratively shift values of test_X by replacing the last value with the prediction.

We do this untill we exhaust the length of test_y.

[!NOTE] Follow lectures from IBM course on Time-Series Analysis or Deeplearning Specialization by DeepLearning.ai

on Coursera for a detailed explanation.

In [ ]:
def make_predictions(test_x,model,n_steps=len(test_y)):

    test_x = np.array(test_x)
    test_x_init = test_x.copy().reshape(1,-1,1)

    predictions = []

    for _ in range(n_steps):

        pred = model.predict(test_x_init)
        predictions.append(pred)
        test_x_init[:,:-1,:] = test_x_init[:,1:,:]
        test_x_init[:,-1,:] = pred

    predictions = np.array(predictions).reshape(-1,1)

    return predictions

def fit_LSTM(train_X, train_Y, cell_units, epochs):
    """
    Fit LSTM to data train_X, train_y 
    
    arguments
    ---------
    train_X (array): input sequence samples for training 
    train_y (list): next step in sequence targets
    cell_units (int): number of hidden units for LSTM cells  
    epochs (int): number of training epochs   
    """
    
    # initialize model
    model = Sequential() 
    
    # construct a LSTM layer with specified number of hidden units
    # per cell and desired sequence input format 
    model.add(LSTM(cell_units, input_shape=(train_X.shape[1],1))) #,return_sequences= True))
    #model.add(LSTM(cell_units_l2, input_shape=(train_X.shape[1],1)))
    
    # add an output layer to make final predictions 
    model.add(Dense(1))
    
    # define the loss function / optimization strategy, and fit
    # the model with the desired number of passes over the data (epochs) 
    model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam')
    model.fit(train_X, train_Y, epochs=epochs, batch_size=64, verbose=0)
    
    return model

Summary -¶

Based on the analysis we observe that ARIMA (1,1,0) was able to capture the trend better than the exponential smoothing. We used ARIMA (1,1,0) since the series was not stationary until first differencing. Further exploration for a better choice of (p,d,q) variables is one of the future objectives.

A simple implementation of forecasting using Prophet was also used for comparison.

In the cased of deep learning methods, we used a simple RNN architecture (input size = 20, cell units = 25, epochs = 500) to make predictions. However the model badly underfits demanding fine tuning. The performance was improved when the model used LSTM (cell units = 100, epochs = 1000) but still needs improvement.

The future goal of this study is to work on inference methods and more statistical tests to make the results more robust. Use fine-tuning and cross-validation in neural network based forecasting for better predictions.
